= Introduction

This document tests the Phase 4 implementation of plot support in knot. We use the `typst()` function from the `knot.r.package` to serialize ggplot2 plots.

= Simple ggplot2 Plot

Let's create a simple scatter plot with the iris dataset.

```{r}
#| eval: true
#| echo: true
#| output: true
library(ggplot2)

gg <- ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width, color = Species)) +
  geom_point(size = 3, alpha = 0.7) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(
    title = "Iris Dataset: Sepal Dimensions",
    x = "Sepal Length (cm)",
    y = "Sepal Width (cm)"
  )

typst(gg)
```

= Plot with Custom Dimensions

Here we specify custom width, height, and DPI for higher resolution.

```{r}
#| eval: true
#| echo: true
#| output: true
gg2 <- ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = wt, y = mpg)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = factor(cyl)), size = 4) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "black", linetype = "dashed") +
  theme_light() +
  labs(
    title = "Miles per Gallon vs Weight",
    x = "Weight (1000 lbs)",
    y = "Miles per Gallon",
    color = "Cylinders"
  )

typst(gg2, width = 8, height = 5, dpi = 300)
```

= DataFrame + Plot (Combined Output)

This chunk outputs both a summary table and a plot.

```{r}
#| eval: true
#| echo: true
#| output: true
# Create summary table
summary_df <- data.frame(
  Statistic = c("Mean Sepal Length", "Mean Sepal Width", "Sample Size"),
  Value = c(
    mean(iris$Sepal.Length),
    mean(iris$Sepal.Width),
    nrow(iris)
  )
)

typst(summary_df)

# Create distribution plot
gg3 <- ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, fill = Species)) +
  geom_histogram(alpha = 0.6, position = "identity", bins = 20) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of Sepal Length by Species",
    x = "Sepal Length (cm)",
    y = "Frequency"
  )

typst(gg3, width = 9, height = 4)
```

= Boxplot Example

Visualizing distributions with boxplots.

```{r}
#| eval: true
#| echo: true
#| output: true
gg4 <- ggplot(iris, aes(x = Species, y = Petal.Length, fill = Species)) +
  geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.7) +
  theme_classic() +
  labs(
    title = "Petal Length Distribution by Species",
    x = "Species",
    y = "Petal Length (cm)"
  ) +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

typst(gg4)
```

= Faceted Plot

Using facets to show multiple subplots.

```{r}
#| eval: true
#| echo: true
#| output: true
gg5 <- ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = Species), size = 2) +
  facet_wrap(~ Species) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(
    title = "Sepal Dimensions by Species (Faceted)",
    x = "Sepal Length (cm)",
    y = "Sepal Width (cm)"
  )

typst(gg5, width = 10, height = 4)
```

= Conclusion

All plot types have been successfully rendered using the `typst()` function. The plots are cached and integrated into the Typst document.

*Features tested:*
- Simple scatter plots
- Custom dimensions (width, height, dpi)
- Combined DataFrame + Plot output
- Boxplots
- Faceted plots
